        <paragraph>A 2D physics body that can't be moved by external forces. When moved manually, it affects other bodies in its path.</paragraph>
        <section classes="classref-introduction-group" ids="description" names="description">
            <title>Description</title>
            <paragraph>An animatable 2D physics body. It can't be moved by external forces or contacts, but can be moved manually by other means such as code, <reference internal="True" refuri="class_animationmixer#class-animationmixer"><inline classes="std std-ref">AnimationMixer</inline></reference>s (with <reference internal="True" refuri="class_animationmixer#class-animationmixer-property-callback-mode-process"><inline classes="std std-ref">AnimationMixer.callback_mode_process</inline></reference> set to <reference internal="True" refuri="class_animationmixer#class-animationmixer-constant-animation-callback-mode-process-physics"><inline classes="std std-ref">AnimationMixer.ANIMATION_CALLBACK_MODE_PROCESS_PHYSICS</inline></reference>), and <reference internal="True" refuri="class_remotetransform2d#class-remotetransform2d"><inline classes="std std-ref">RemoteTransform2D</inline></reference>.</paragraph>
            <paragraph>When <strong>AnimatableBody2D</strong> is moved, its linear and angular velocity are estimated and used to affect other physics bodies in its path. This makes it useful for moving platforms, doors, and other moving objects.</paragraph>
